{{Main|Jam band festivals|List of music festivals}} {{Infobox |name = List of jam band festivals |bodystyle = |titlestyle = |abovestyle = background:#E9967A; |subheaderstyle = |title = |above = List of jam band festivals |image = [[File:All Good Festival 2011.jpg|300px]] |caption = |headerstyle = background:#EDC9AF; |header1 = General Information
|label2 = Related genres |data2 = [[Psychedelic rock]], [[Electronic music|electronic]], [[folk rock]], [[blues rock]], [[jazz fusion]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[southern rock]], [[progressive rock]], [[acid jazz]], [[hip hop]], [[hard rock]], and [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] |label3 = Location |data3 = [[United States]] <small>(origin)</small>, worldwide |label4 = Related events |data4 = [[:Category:Jam band festivals]], [[list of music festivals]], [[free festival]], [[rock festival]], [[electronic music festival]], [[reggae festival]] |label5 = Related topics |data5 = [[Deadhead]], [[hippie]] }}
This is a '''list of jam band music festivals'''. This list may have some overlap with [[list of historic rock festivals]] and [[list of reggae festivals]]. [[Jam bands]] are musical groups who relate to a unique fan culture that began in the 1960s with [[Grateful Dead]] (see [[deadheads]]), and continued with [[The Allman Brothers Band]], which had lengthy jams at concerts. The performances of these [[Musical ensemble|bands]] typically feature extended [[musical improvisation]] ("[[jam session|jams]]") over rhythmic [[groove (music)|groove]]s and [[vamp (music)|chord patterns]], and long sets of music that can often cross genre boundaries.<ref name="wiajb">{{cite web|url=http://www.jambands.com/jamband.html |title=What is a jam band? |accessdate=2007-02-02 |publisher=Jambands.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124191643/http://www.jambands.com/jamband.html |archivedate=2007-01-24 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
While the seminal group Grateful Dead are categorized as [[psychedelic rock]],<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/psychedelic/bands/gratefuldead.html The Grateful Dead] ''Britannica Online'', Retrieved 17 September 2007</ref> by the 1990s the term "jam band" was being used for groups playing a variety of rock-related genres, and [[jam band festival]] lineups could include [[blues]], [[country music]], [[traditional music|folk music]], and [[funk]]. Today the term even includes some groups completely outside rock, such as those playing [[world music]], [[electronic music]], [[progressive bluegrass]], and [[jazz fusion]].<ref name="wiajb"/> A unique feature of the jam band scene is bands allowing fan taping or digital recording of live concerts.
